net.sf.mmm.util.datatype.api.phone

Class InternationalCallPrefix

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.sf.mmm.util.lang.api.AbstractDatatype
      • net.sf.mmm.util.lang.api.AbstractSimpleDatatypeBase<V>
        • net.sf.mmm.util.lang.api.AbstractSimpleDatatype<String>
          • net.sf.mmm.util.datatype.api.phone.InternationalCallPrefix
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, AttributeReadValue<String>, Datatype, SimpleDatatype<String>

    public final class InternationalCallPrefix
extends AbstractSimpleDatatype<String>
    This class is a Datatype that represents the international call prefix (also called exit code or IDD code) for a phone number. It is the sequence that has to be dialed before the PhoneCountryCode to make an international call. The InternationalCallPrefix is specific for the county the caller is dialing from. Therefore it is typically indicated by the plus sign (+) in internationalized phone numbers. The InternationalCallPrefix is typically "00" as suggested by the international telecommunications union (ITU). However, some countries have other codes like "011" (NANPA). In Finland there are multiple international call prefixes for different phone carriers. The longest prefix is (so far) 5 digits.
    Since:
    1.0.0
    Author:
    Joerg Hohwiller (hohwille at users.sourceforge.net)
